00:07:37.250 --> 00:07:41.500
&gt;&gt;Adam: Usually it's just to indicate that
there's another screen underneath it that's

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.069
going to take you someplace
different.

00:07:43.069 --> 00:07:49.410
&gt;&gt;Ian: [sharp intake of breath] I think that's
true, but why in particular the right caret

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:56.770
because the action
for going to another screen has nothing to

00:07:56.770 --> 00:07:58.960
do with anything to the right of what you
see right--

00:07:58.960 --> 00:07:59.960
&gt;&gt;Reto: Hmm.

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:00.960
That's true.

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:04.639
&gt;&gt;Ian:-- so I guess what I'm implying is that
maybe that's a carryover from you know some

00:08:04.639 --> 00:08:08.430
other type of system where
the animation is different or---

00:08:08.430 --> 00:08:12.000
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, it feels that way, like as though
maybe the developers have used a different

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.110
operating system which
perhaps when you hit right everything slides

00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:17.541
from left to right so that you can sort of--

00:08:17.541 --> 00:08:19.009
&gt;&gt;Adam: You mean an operating system like
Gingerbread?

00:08:19.009 --> 00:08:20.069
&gt;&gt;Reto: Possibly.

00:08:20.069 --> 00:08:23.160
[laughs] Possibly a different operating system
like Gingerbread.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:28.520
&gt;&gt;Adam: So one of the other elements here
as well is--the design guide I believe explicitly

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:32.320
calls out the case of
settings as something that shouldn't be either

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:36.930
frequent, important or typical--so realistically
that should be in an

00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:37.930
overflow--

00:08:37.930 --> 00:08:38.930
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly.

00:08:38.930 --> 00:08:40.669
&gt;&gt;Adam:--but it's entirely understandable
in a case like this where that's the only

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:45.350
option that would be in the
overflow there's sort of a simple judgment

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:46.680
call to be made there.

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:47.680
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:48.680
I agree.

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:51.929
I think in this case though I mean what you've
got here if nothing else is just taking up

00:08:51.929 --> 00:08:52.929
more screen real estate.

00:08:52.929 --> 00:08:55.480
It's something else the user has to look at
and understand.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:58.420
Like you see a cog and you're
like "What does the cog mean?"

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:01.940
Which means you need to press it to find out,
and I think just having that overflow

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:06.769
menu is kind of where users are expecting
things like settings to be so it makes it

00:09:06.769 --> 00:09:10.829
sort of cognitively easy to
understand what you're supposed to do because--and

00:09:10.829 --> 00:09:14.040
again this is something I tend to go on a
bit at length but it's

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:18.309
creating that magical experience where as
soon as you launch the app, you should be

00:09:18.309 --> 00:09:21.839
doing whatever it is the app is
designed to do straightaway.

00:09:21.839 --> 00:09:25.160
So you shouldn't have to spend time exploring
the app and figuring out how it all works

00:09:25.160 --> 00:09:26.720
in order to understand it's value.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:30.999
Like people are going to install this, start
using it, and the less they have to

00:09:30.999 --> 00:09:35.160
think about how things work, it's kind of
the more of a magical experience it is for

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:36.160
those people.

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:39.249
&gt;&gt;Adam: That's definitely true, but what you
need to watch out for as well--and I think

00:09:39.249 --> 00:09:44.071
what developers look at when they
make decisions such as this-- is what do you

00:09:44.071 --> 00:09:47.550
do--a lot of developers will count clicks--

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:48.550
&gt;&gt;Reto: Hmm.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:52.480
&gt;&gt;Adam:-- in terms of how deep an action is
or how complex the process for getting to

00:09:52.480 --> 00:09:54.420
a particular action is.

00:09:54.420 --> 00:09:57.920
And I
think in this case the decision was made "Okay,

00:09:57.920 --> 00:09:59.200
one click is better than two."

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:00.200
&gt;&gt;Reto: Mmm.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:06.410
&gt;&gt;Adam: So--but that's not always the only
metric you should use when deciding on UI

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:07.410
elements such as this.

00:10:07.410 --> 00:10:10.350
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, I think what you were saying
earlier is kind of the key there is--it's--you

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:12.550
want to make it really
quick and easy to do the things that are most

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:14.089
important for your app.

00:10:14.089 --> 00:10:15.279
Anything that you don't want people to do
all

00:10:15.279 --> 00:10:17.439
the time, can afford to live further away.

